programmer that wants to or is being told to use R? Yeah. So I think the most important thing is,

00:20:35.760 --> 00:20:41.680
if you are, you have to embrace it. You have to acknowledge that it is a different language.

00:20:42.560 --> 00:20:50.719
As a SaaS programmer, like I said, I used to be a SaaS programmer. I think having this

00:20:51.599 --> 00:20:58.239
understanding about functional programming, about the syntax around it, it's very important. I think

00:20:58.239 --> 00:21:04.000
you just have to learn and train yourself. I remember that at the beginning of my career,

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:10.479
switching to R, I just practiced a lot. And the easiest way to practice is the data step stuff,

00:21:10.479 --> 00:21:18.640
the cleaning stuff up and making the data ready. That, to me, was an easy entry point.

00:21:19.439 --> 00:21:25.439
So if you ask me what is my favorite R package, it has to be dplyr, because that was my first

00:21:27.439 --> 00:21:32.880
package that I used a long time ago, and I still know how to do it, even though I do

00:21:33.839 --> 00:21:40.640
more of Shiny stuff now. But then you will level up. I think after dplyr, you learn about, okay,

00:21:40.640 --> 00:21:44.400
then how do I do this in base? Because now if you're making R package, you want to make sure,

00:21:44.719 --> 00:21:49.520
does it really make sense to bring the whole dplyr in, or can I get this away with some base

00:21:49.520 --> 00:21:55.920
