00:44:47.199 --> 00:44:51.760
treat these projects as a learning exercise or something that you should put on your resume?

00:44:56.560 --> 00:45:00.639
I would say both. Do you look at projects and stuff when you look at applications?

00:45:01.679 --> 00:45:08.959
Yes, I do. I do actually. I usually ask people like what is their either recent project or their

00:45:10.080 --> 00:45:15.520
most proud project that they work on? Because again, it could be small, it could be big.

00:45:16.320 --> 00:45:23.439
What I do is that if I have a project, like my side project, I just want to do this one thing.

00:45:24.399 --> 00:45:31.600
And yes, it's a good learning experience, right? So, I think I recall I have a package that

00:45:31.600 --> 00:45:39.679
I made where I want to streamline my working when I have a lot of different dependencies.

00:45:40.639 --> 00:45:45.360
So, if you work in a product that has a lot of dependencies, then sometimes things can be

00:45:46.399 --> 00:45:52.239
quite hard to switch different branches, different feature branches, and so on. So,

00:45:52.239 --> 00:45:56.320
I make a package from there. But then I just thought it was a good product, so I just push

00:45:56.320 --> 00:46:01.120
it into GitHub and see if anybody else is interested. And then, yes, that would be a good

00:46:01.679 --> 00:46:06.560
adding to your resume because now it's in there. And if you want to take it to the next level,

00:46:06.560 --> 00:46:13.600
push it to CRAN, and then it can really become public. But I would say both. If you can use it

00:46:13.600 --> 00:46:18.159
for learning, but then as you use it for learning, hopefully the ideas will come in. All right,

00:46:18.159 --> 00:46:24.719
this looks like an interesting technique to do this certain problem that may be closer to your

00:46:24.719 --> 00:46:32.639
field. And if you see that opportunity, pursue it. Just try. Make something. That's the great

00:46:32.639 --> 00:46:38.399
thing about R2. There's a lot of documentation about how to make R package. If you're not into

00:46:38.399 --> 00:46:44.000
R package, you're more like a web guy, deploy ShinyApps. Shinyapps.io, I think Posit also,

00:46:44.639 --> 00:46:50.959
you guys are the owner, right? Shinyapps.io, if I'm not mistaken. Yeah, it's free. It's free for,

00:46:50.959 --> 00:46:55.840
like, I think they have a free tier. And then if it's become bigger and you want to scale it,

00:46:56.800 --> 00:47:04.080
I think there's some fees. But for the starter, it's free. And I do this too. I just deploy stuff

00:47:04.080 --> 00:47:12.159
to Shinyapps.io. Oh, I will say the evolution of Shinyapps.io, Posit Connect Cloud, which is

00:47:12.800 --> 00:47:18.800
even easier. I mean, I have Shinyapp deployed to Posit Connect Cloud because I too have personal

00:47:18.800 --> 00:47:25.679
projects. And you really just, like, hook it up to a repo. You tell it which dot R file is your app

00:47:25.679 --> 00:47:32.320
or which Shiny file is your app. You create a manifest, and you're done. And then every time

00:47:32.320 --> 00:47:38.000
you push to your repo as an update, it immediately updates your live Shiny app. Could not be easier.

00:47:39.199 --> 00:47:45.919
Chef's kiss, I would recommend. Either that or Shinyapps.io. All right. That was an amazing

